d also be removed. Currently, NI is paid at a rate of eight per cent on all earnings up to Â£50,268 and two per cent on income above that threshold. That rate would instead be increased to eight per cent, raising Â£20 billion.Capital gains tax would also be equalised with income tax rates to bring in Â£16 billion, while inheritance tax reliefs on farmland, business property and pension pots would be axed to raise Â£4 billion.Council tax rates would be reformed to become â€œfairerâ€, meaning rates in more expensive areas could double.Lastly, a â€œjackpot taxâ€ on what the proposal deems â€œextreme wealthâ€ would raise Â£10 billion a year.Labourâ€™s manifesto contains proposals for tax rises worth a total of Â£8.6 billion.The party has insisted it will not raise income tax, National Insurance or VAT.But senior figures have refused to rule out raising capital gains tax or council tax, saying only that there are â€œno plansâ€ to do so."
